\section{The play viewer}
\label{sec:play}

The interactive viewer uses [[curses]] to show one commit at a
time with vi-style navigation.
We chose [[curses]] over a prompt-based loop because single-keypress
navigation feels natural for browsing a log---the user never needs
to press Enter.
Since [[curses]] is a standard library module on Unix systems and
learnlog targets university lab machines (Linux), this is a
pragmatic choice.

The viewer state is simple: the current commit index and a vertical
scroll offset within the commit's content.
We cache the detail for the currently displayed commit to avoid
re-fetching on every scroll.

\subsection{The [[PlaybackViewer]] class}

<<play viewer>>=
class PlaybackViewer:
    """Interactive curses-based commit viewer.

    Displays commits one at a time with vi-style navigation:
    ``H``/``L`` for previous/next commit, ``j``/``k`` for
    scrolling within a commit, ``q`` to quit.
    """

    def __init__(self, repo, commits, start_index=0,
                 filter_learnlog=True):
        self.repo = repo
        self.commits = commits
        self.index = start_index
        self.scroll = 0
        self.filter_learnlog = filter_learnlog
        self._detail_cache = {}

    <<player methods>>
@

\subsection{Running the viewer}

The [[run]] method enters curses mode and drives the main loop.
We use [[curses.wrapper]] to ensure the terminal is restored
even if an exception occurs.

<<player methods>>=
def run(self):
    """Enter curses mode and run the interactive viewer."""
    import curses
    curses.wrapper(self._main_loop)
@

\subsection{The main loop}

Each iteration draws the screen and waits for a keypress.
We redraw on every key because the state may have changed.

We call [[curses.use_default_colors]] so that the viewer inherits
the terminal's native background and foreground colours instead
of forcing white-on-black.
This respects light themes, transparency, and custom colour
schemes---details that matter when learnlog runs on diverse
student and teacher machines.

<<player methods>>=
def _main_loop(self, stdscr):
    """Main event loop inside curses."""
    import curses
    curses.use_default_colors()
    curses.curs_set(0)
    stdscr.clear()

    while True:
        self._draw(stdscr)
        key = stdscr.getch()
        if not self._handle_key(key):
            break
@

\subsection{Drawing the screen}

The screen has three regions: a header showing position and
commit subject, the scrollable content area with the commit
message and diff, and a footer with key bindings.

We build the content as a list of lines, then display the
portion that fits in the terminal window starting from the
scroll offset.
This approach avoids the complexity of [[curses]] pads while
handling arbitrarily long diffs.

<<player methods>>=
def _get_detail(self, commit_hash):
    """Fetch and cache the ``git show`` output."""
    if commit_hash not in self._detail_cache:
        self._detail_cache[commit_hash] = \
            get_commit_detail(
                self.repo, commit_hash,
                self.filter_learnlog,
            )
    return self._detail_cache[commit_hash]
@

We cache the [[git show]] output because fetching it shells out to
Git.
Without caching, every scroll keystroke would re-run the command,
making the viewer sluggish on large repositories.

<<player methods>>=
def _draw(self, stdscr):
    """Render the current commit to the screen."""
    stdscr.erase()
    height, width = stdscr.getmaxyx()

    commit = self.commits[self.index]
    detail = self._get_detail(commit["hash"])
    if detail is None:
        detail = "(learnlog internal run)"

    <<draw header>>
    <<build content lines>>
    <<draw content area>>
    <<draw footer>>

    stdscr.refresh()
@

The header shows the position in the commit list, the short
hash, and the commit subject.
We truncate to the terminal width to avoid curses errors.

<<draw header>>=
header = (
    f"[{self.index + 1}/{len(self.commits)}] "
    f"{commit['hash'][:7]} "
    f"— {commit['subject']}"
)
header = header[:width - 1]
try:
    import curses
    stdscr.addstr(0, 0, header, curses.A_REVERSE)
    stdscr.addstr(
        0, len(header),
        " " * (width - len(header) - 1),
        curses.A_REVERSE,
    )
except curses.error:
    pass
@

The content is the reordered [[git show]] output, which places
the diff before the commit message so that code changes appear
first.
We split into lines for scrollable display.

<<build content lines>>=
content_lines = detail.split("\n")
@

We display lines starting from the scroll offset, filling
the area between the header (row~0) and the footer
(last row).

<<draw content area>>=
content_start = 1
content_end = height - 2
visible = content_end - content_start

self.scroll = max(
    0,
    min(self.scroll,
        len(content_lines) - visible),
)

for i in range(visible):
    line_idx = self.scroll + i
    if line_idx >= len(content_lines):
        break
    line = content_lines[line_idx][:width - 1]
    try:
        stdscr.addstr(content_start + i, 0, line)
    except curses.error:
        pass
@

The footer shows key bindings.
It sits on the last row of the terminal.

<<draw footer>>=
footer = (
    " H/\u2190: prev  L/\u2192: next  "
    "j/\u2193: down  k/\u2191: up  "
    "g: first  G: last  q: quit"
)
footer = footer[:width - 1]
try:
    import curses
    stdscr.addstr(
        height - 1, 0, footer, curses.A_REVERSE
    )
    remaining = width - len(footer) - 1
    if remaining > 0:
        stdscr.addstr(
            height - 1, len(footer),
            " " * remaining,
            curses.A_REVERSE,
        )
except curses.error:
    pass
@


\subsection{Handling key presses}

The key handler updates the viewer state and returns [[False]]
when the user presses [[q]] to quit.
We support both the letter keys ([[H]], [[L]], [[j]], [[k]])
and arrow keys for accessibility.

<<player methods>>=
def _handle_key(self, key):
    """Process a keypress.  Return ``False`` to quit."""
    import curses

    if key in (ord("q"), ord("Q")):
        return False
    elif key in (ord("h"), ord("H"), curses.KEY_LEFT):
        if self.index > 0:
            self.index -= 1
            self.scroll = 0
    elif key in (ord("l"), ord("L"), curses.KEY_RIGHT):
        if self.index < len(self.commits) - 1:
            self.index += 1
            self.scroll = 0
    elif key in (ord("j"), curses.KEY_DOWN):
        self.scroll += 1
    elif key in (ord("k"), curses.KEY_UP):
        self.scroll = max(0, self.scroll - 1)
    elif key == ord("g"):
        self.index = 0
        self.scroll = 0
    elif key == ord("G"):
        self.index = len(self.commits) - 1
        self.scroll = 0

    return True
@

We test the key handler logic without a real curses screen
by calling it directly with key codes:

<<test functions>>=
def test_handle_key_quit():
    from learnlog.cli import PlaybackViewer
    viewer = PlaybackViewer(None, [{"hash": "a"}], 0)
    assert viewer._handle_key(ord("q")) is False

def test_handle_key_navigation():
    from learnlog.cli import PlaybackViewer
    commits = [
        {"hash": "a"}, {"hash": "b"}, {"hash": "c"}
    ]
    viewer = PlaybackViewer(None, commits, 0)
    viewer._handle_key(ord("l"))
    assert viewer.index == 1
    viewer._handle_key(ord("l"))
    assert viewer.index == 2
    viewer._handle_key(ord("l"))
    assert viewer.index == 2  # at end, stays
    viewer._handle_key(ord("h"))
