\subsection{The [[set-remote]] command}
\label{sec:set-remote}

The [[export]] command (\cref{sec:export}) produces a portable bundle
file, but for workflows where the destination is a remote Git
repository---such as a university GitLab instance---repeatedly
exporting and manually delivering bundles is tedious.
A simpler alternative is to configure a remote on the [[.learnlog/]]
repository and push directly.

The [[set-remote]] command configures the destination; [[push]]
(\cref{sec:push}) delivers the data.
We always use the remote name [[origin]] because [[.learnlog/]] is a
single-purpose recording artefact with one destination---there is no
practical need for multiple remotes.

If [[origin]] already exists we update its URL with
[[git remote set-url]]; otherwise we create it with
[[git remote add]].
We detect the current state by checking the exit code of
[[git remote get-url]], which fails when the remote does not exist.

<<typer commands>>=
@app.command(name="set-remote")
def set_remote(
    url: Annotated[
        str,
        typer.Argument(
            help="URL of the remote repository.",
        ),
    ],
    directory: Annotated[
        Optional[pathlib.Path],
        typer.Option(
            "--dir", "-C",
            help="Directory containing .learnlog/.",
        ),
    ] = None,
):
    """Set the remote origin URL for the learnlog repository."""
    workdir = resolve_workdir(directory)
    repo = LearnlogRepo(workdir)

    check = repo.git("remote", "get-url", "origin")
    if check.returncode == 0:
        result = repo.git(
            "remote", "set-url", "origin", url
        )
    else:
        result = repo.git(
            "remote", "add", "origin", url
        )

    if result.returncode != 0:
        raise SystemExit(
            f"Failed to set remote: {result.stderr}"
        )

    typer.echo(f"Remote origin set to {url}")
@

